{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499918"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1583"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.05,0.09,0.27,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54028"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39500"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"573"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42346"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54028"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner for a skin check. He has a number of pigmented lesions on his trunk and he is not sure how long they have been present for. He has not noticed any recent changes in any of them. He is otherwise well with no significant medical history. He takes no regular medications and is a lifetime non-smoker. He has worked for many years as a labourer on building sites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinician decides that one in particular requires a closer examination with the dermatoscope (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the features that are present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Asymmetry, blue-white structures, atypical network","Symmetry, blue-white structures, atypical network","Asymmetry, blue-white structures, typical network","Asymmetry, normal structures, atypical network","Symmetry, normal structures, typical network"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lesion scores three out of three on the dematoscopy 3-point rule for pigmented skin lesions. The rule gives one point for positive findings of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymmetry in the horizontal or vertical plane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtypical network: pigment network with irregular holes and thick lines\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlue-white structures: any type of blue and/or white colour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVisual examples of these findings are available on DermNetNZ (Three-point checklist | DermNet NZ. Available from: \u003Ca href=\u0022https://dermnetnz.org/cme/dermoscopy-course/three-point-checklist/\u0022\u003Ehttps://dermnetnz.org/cme/dermoscopy-course/three-point-checklist/\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main aim of the 3-point checklist is to determine whether the lesion examined should undergo a biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lesion shown (image):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIs asymmetrical\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas blue/white structures\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas an irregular pigment network\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of 0-1 on the 3-point rule suggests the lesion could benign. However, given this lesion scored three out of three, an excision biopsy was performed. The histology returned as a fully excised seborrheic keratosis with benign melanocytic naevus. This is known as a combined lesion, where two separate lesions have collided to produce more atypical appearance, which warranted further investigation with an excisional biopsy.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll pigmented lesions of concern should be excised completely with a 2mm surgical margin.\u00a0The aim is to exclude melanoma and the 2mm margin allows room for injection with blue dye or radio-active dye if patient is subsequently confirmed to have melanoma and requires sentinel lymph node biopsy.\u00a0 Removal of lesion with \u0026gt;2mm margin may hinder the accuracy of sentinel lymph node biopsy while partial biopsy of the lesion may not demonstrate the true depth (Breslow thickness) of the melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The three point dermatoscopy checklist is presence of asymmetry, any blue/white structures, and atypical/pigmented network - for lesions which score a total of three, an excision biopsy should be performed."],"references":["Weber P, Tschandl P, Sinz C, et al. Dermatoscopy of Neoplastic Skin Lesions: Recent Advances, Updates, and Revisions. Curr Treat Options Oncol. 2018;19:56. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6153581/","Dermoscopy three-point checklist. In: DermNet NZ [Internet]. 2008. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/cme/dermoscopy-course/three-point-checklist/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39500"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1563"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21058"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1563"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4dae708f-19f2-4779-a167-65fe455f9dee.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4dae708f-19f2-4779-a167-65fe455f9dee.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":386,"height":366}},{"type":"media","id":"21058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21058"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/43s1Ll0h7Xp2TIwPkVJDtGeEFOwkfz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/43s1Ll0h7Xp2TIwPkVJDtGeEFOwkfz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":384,"height":357}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39500"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T08:40:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T08:41:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1583"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54028"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.eme